\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{siunitx}

\begin{document}

When a charged particle moves at an angle $\theta$ to the field direction, the particle will move in a helical path. The vector velocity $\mathbf{v}$ of the particle can be resolved into two components, one parallel to $\mathbf{B}$ and one perpendicular to it:
\[
v_{\parallel} = v \cos \theta \quad \text{and} \quad v_{\perp} = v \sin \theta
\]

The parallel component determines the pitch of the helix, that is, the distance between the adjacent turns. The perpendicular component determines the radius $r$ of the helix:

\[
v = \sqrt{\frac{2K}{m}} = \sqrt{\frac{2 \times 1 \times 1.6 \times 10^{-19}}{9.1 \times 10^{-31}}} = 5.93 \times 10^{5} \, \text{m/s}
\]

\[
r = \frac{mv \sin \theta}{|q| B} = \frac{9.1 \times 10^{-31} \times 5.93 \times 10^{5} \times \sin 60^\circ}{1.6 \times 10^{-19} \times 10^{-3}} = 2.92 \times 10^{-3} \, \text{m} = 2.92 \, \text{mm}
\]

Time period $T$:
\[
T = \frac{2\pi m}{|q| B} = \frac{2\pi \times 9.1 \times 10^{-31}}{1.6 \times 10^{-19} \times 10^{-3}} = 3.57 \times 10^{-8} \, \text{s}
\]

Pitch:
\[
\text{Pitch} = (v \cos \theta) T = 5.93 \times 10^{5} \times \cos 60^\circ \times 3.57 \times 10^{-8} = 0.1 \, \text{m}
\]

\end{document}
```

