\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{graphicx}

\begin{document}

\section*{Magnetic Field Due to a Current Element}

\subsection*{(a) Magnetic Field from a Finite Wire}

Consider a typical current element \( dx \). The magnitude of the contribution \( dB \) of this element to the magnetic field at point \( P \) is found from the Biot–Savart law and is given by

\begin{equation}
    dB = \frac{\mu_0 i \, dx \sin \theta}{4 \pi R^2}
\end{equation}

\begin{figure}[h]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth]{fig13_22.pdf}
    \caption{Magnetic induction due to a current-carrying wire of finite length.}
    \label{fig:magnetic_induction}
\end{figure}

Since the direction of the contribution \( dB \) at point \( P \) for all such elements is identical, i.e., at right angles to the plane of the paper, the resultant field is obtained by integrating \( dB \) from \( A \) to \( D \) in (1). Writing \( \sin \theta = \frac{r}{R} \), we have

\begin{align}
    B &= \int dB = \frac{\mu_0 i r}{4 \pi} \int_{-a}^{b} \frac{dx}{(x^2 + r^2)^{3/2}} \\
    &= \frac{\mu_0 i r}{4 \pi r^2} \left[ \frac{x}{(x^2 + r^2)^{1/2}} \right]_{-a}^{b} \\
    \therefore B &= \frac{\mu_0 i}{4 \pi r} (\cos \theta_1 + \cos \theta_2)
\end{align}

\subsection*{(b) Magnetic Field from an Infinite Wire}

For an infinite wire, \( \theta_1 \to 0 \) and \( \theta_2 \to 0 \). In this limit, equation (2) becomes

\begin{equation}
    B = \frac{\mu_0 i}{2 \pi r}
\end{equation}

which is the expression for the magnetic field due to a long wire.

\end{document}
```

