\section*{Magnetic Field Due to a Square Conducting Loop}

The magnetic field $B_1$ due to a current $i$ in one segment of a square loop is given by (see Fig. 13.23):

\begin{equation}
B_1 = \frac{\mu_0 i}{4 \pi R} (\cos \theta_1 + \cos \theta_2)
\end{equation}

By setting $\theta_1 = \theta_2 = 45^\circ$ and $R = \frac{a}{2}$, we have:

\begin{equation}
B_1 = \frac{\mu_0 i \sqrt{2}}{\pi a}
\end{equation}

The fields due to the four sides of the square are equal and additive. Therefore, the net field $B$ at the center of the square is:

\begin{equation}
B = 4B_1 = \frac{2\sqrt{2} \mu_0 i}{\pi a}
\end{equation}

