\usepackage{amssymb}
\begin{document}

\section*{Magnetic Induction Due to Current-Carrying Wires}

\subsection*{(a) Magnetic Induction from Straight Wires}

The magnetic induction due to straight wires is given by:

\begin{equation}
B_1 = \frac{\mu_0 i}{4 \pi R} + \frac{\mu_0 i}{4 \pi R} = \frac{\mu_0 i}{2 \pi R}
\end{equation}

because the straight wires are of infinite length only on the left side. The induction at point \( O \) due to the semicircular portion is:

\begin{equation}
B_2 = \frac{\mu_0 i}{4 R}
\end{equation}

The total magnetic induction \( B \) is the sum of \( B_1 \) and \( B_2 \):

\begin{equation}
B = B_1 + B_2 = \frac{\mu_0 i}{2 \pi R} + \frac{\mu_0 i}{4 R} = \frac{\mu_0 i}{4 \pi R}(2 + \pi)
\end{equation}

\subsection*{(b) Contribution from the Straight Portions}

The straight portions of the wire do not contribute to the field at \( O \) as the current is directed towards \( C \) and makes an angle \( \theta = 0^\circ \), for which the Biot–Savart formula gives \( B = 0 \). Thus, the entire induction comes from the semicircular portion of the wire, for which:

\begin{equation}
B = \frac{\mu_0 i}{4 R}
\end{equation}

\end{document}
```

