\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{amssymb}
\usepackage{graphicx}

\begin{document}

\section*{Magnetic Induction at the Centre of a Current-Carrying Regular $n$-Sided Polygon}

\subsection*{(a) Magnetic Induction for a Regular $n$-Sided Polygon}

Let the angle $\theta$ be subtended at the center by one side $AC$ of a regular $n$-sided polygon, as shown in Fig. 13.25. Then,

\[
\theta = \frac{2\pi}{n} \quad \text{or} \quad \frac{\theta}{2} = \frac{\pi}{n} \tag{1}
\]

The magnetic induction due to one side $AC$ at the center $O$ is given by

\[
B_1 = \frac{\mu_0 i}{4\pi r} (\cos \alpha + \cos \alpha) = \frac{\mu_0 i \cos \alpha}{2\pi r} \tag{2}
\]

where $r$ is the distance of $O$ from $AC$. The field $B$ due to $n$ sides will be additive and is given by

\[
B = n B_1 = \frac{\mu_0 n i \cos \alpha}{2\pi r} \tag{3}
\]

Now, $r = a \sin \alpha$, so that in (3)

\[
\frac{\cos \alpha}{r} = \frac{\cos \alpha}{a \sin \alpha} = \frac{1}{a} \cot \alpha = \frac{1}{a} \tan \left( \frac{\theta}{2} \right) = \frac{1}{a} \tan \left( \frac{\pi}{n} \right) \tag{4}
\]

where we have used (1). Using (4) in (3),

\[
B = \frac{\mu_0 n i}{2\pi a \tan \left( \frac{\pi}{n} \right)} \tag{5}
\]

\subsection*{(b) Limit as $n \to \infty$}

In the limit $n \to \infty$, $\tan \left( \frac{\pi}{n} \right) \to \frac{\pi}{n}$ and (5) becomes

\[
B = \frac{\mu_0 i}{2a}
\]

an expression which is identical for $B$ for a circular loop. This is reasonable since as $n \to \infty$, the polygon approaches a circle.

\end{document}
```

