\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{graphicx}

\begin{document}

\section*{Biot–Savart Law and Magnetic Induction}

The Biot–Savart law is given by:

\begin{equation}
    d\mathbf{B} = \frac{\mu_0 i}{4\pi} \frac{d\mathbf{s} \times \mathbf{r}}{r^3}
\end{equation}

The magnetic induction \( d\mathbf{B} \) at point \( P \) on the \( z \)-axis due to an element of length \( dl \) of the ring is shown in Fig. 13.26. Resolving \( d\mathbf{B} \) along the \( z \)-axis and perpendicular to it, and summing over all such elements, it is seen that the perpendicular components vanish for reasons of symmetry, and the parallel components get added up. Writing \( dl \) for \( d\mathbf{s} \) and noting that the angle between \( \mathbf{R} \) and \( dl \) is \( 90^\circ \), equation (1) can be written as:

\begin{equation}
    dB_z = (dB) \cos \alpha = \frac{\mu_0 i r dl \cos \alpha}{4\pi r^3}
\end{equation}

Writing \( dl = R d\phi \), where \( \phi \) is the azimuth angle and \( r \cos \alpha = R \), equation (2) becomes:

\begin{equation}
    dB_z = \frac{\mu_0 i R^2 d\phi}{4\pi r^3}
\end{equation}

Integrating, we find:

\begin{equation}
    B_z = B = \int dB_z = \frac{\mu_0 i R^2}{4\pi r^3} \int_0^{2\pi} d\phi = \frac{\mu_0 i R^2}{2(R^2 + z^2)^{3/2}}
\end{equation}

\begin{figure}[h]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth]{fig13_26.png}
    \caption{Magnetic induction on the axis of a current-carrying ring}
    \label{fig:magnetic_induction}
\end{figure}

\end{document}
```

