\usepackage{bm}

\begin{document}

The motion of the proton is equivalent to a current. The current density is given by
\begin{equation}
    \bm{J} = e\bm{v}
\end{equation}

The magnetic field due to a current-carrying circuit is given by the Biot–Savart law
\begin{equation}
    d\bm{B} = \frac{\mu_0 I}{4\pi} \left( \frac{d\bm{l}' \times \bm{R}}{R^3} \right)
\end{equation}
where $d\bm{l}'$ is the circuit element, and $\bm{R}$ is the vector which points from $d\bm{l}'$ to the field point. As there is only one proton, there is no need to integrate to find $\bm{B}$. Replacing the current by the current density $\bm{J}$, the Biot–Savart law is modified as
\begin{equation}
    \bm{B} = \frac{\mu_0}{4\pi} \left( \frac{\bm{J} \times \bm{R}}{R^3} \right)
\end{equation}

Substituting (1) into (3),
\begin{equation}
    \bm{B} = \frac{\mu_0 e}{4\pi} \left( \frac{\bm{v} \times \bm{R}}{R^3} \right)
\end{equation}

Given:
\[
\bm{R} = (\hat{\imath} + 2\hat{\jmath}) \, \text{m}
\]
\[
\bm{v} = (\hat{\imath} + 3\hat{\jmath}) \times 10^4 \, \text{m/s}
\]

Calculating the cross product:
\[
\bm{v} \times \bm{R} = 10^4 \begin{vmatrix}
\hat{\imath} & \hat{\jmath} & \hat{k} \\
1 & 3 & 0 \\
1 & 2 & 0
\end{vmatrix} = -10^4 \hat{k}
\]

Substitute into the expression for $\bm{B}$:
\[
\bm{B} = \frac{4\pi \times 10^{-7}}{4\pi} \times 1.6 \times 10^{-19} \times \left( \frac{-10^4 \hat{k}}{\sqrt{5}^3} \right)
\]

Simplifying:
\[
\bm{B} = 1.43 \times 10^{-23} \hat{k} \, \text{T}
\]

