\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{amssymb}

\begin{document}

\section*{Magnetic Forces on a Coil}

(a) Wire \( PQ \) will produce a field of induction \( B_1 \) at the segment \( AB \) of the coil. The magnitude of \( B_1 \) is given by

\begin{equation}
B_1 = \frac{\mu_0 I_1}{2\pi d}
\end{equation}

The right-hand rule shows that the direction of \( B_1 \) at the segment \( AB \) is downward. Wire \( AB \), which carries a current \( I_2 \), finds itself immersed in an external field of magnetic induction \( B_1 \). A length \( l \) of the segment \( AB \) will experience a sideways magnetic force equal to \( \mathbf{F} = I_2 \mathbf{l} \times \mathbf{B}_1 \), whose magnitude is

\begin{equation}
F_2 = I_2 l B_1 = \frac{\mu_0 l I_1 I_2}{2\pi d}
\end{equation}

The vector rule of signs shows that \( F_2 \) lies in the plane of the coil and points to the right. A similar reasoning shows that the force on the segment \( CD \) will be

\begin{equation}
F_3 = \frac{\mu_0 l I_1 I_2}{2\pi (d+l)}
\end{equation}

to the left in the plane of the coil. There is no force on the segments \( BC \) and \( AD \) as they are perpendicular to \( PQ \). The net force is

\begin{equation}
F_{\text{net}} = \frac{\mu_0 l I_1 I_2}{2\pi} \left[ \frac{1}{d} - \frac{1}{d+l} \right]
\end{equation}

to the right. Substituting the given values,

\begin{align*}
F_{\text{net}} &= \frac{(4\pi \times 10^{-7})(0.05)(1)(4)(10)}{2\pi} \left[ \frac{1}{0.1} - \frac{1}{0.1+0.05} \right] \\
&= 1.335 \times 10^{-5} \, \text{N}
\end{align*}

where we have multiplied Equation (4) by 10 for the number of coils.

\end{document}
```

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{graphicx}

\begin{document}

\section*{Physics Problem and Solution}

\subsection*{(a)}

The flux $\phi_B$ enclosed by the loop, as shown in Fig. 13.30, is given by

\begin{equation}
    \phi_B = B l x
\end{equation}

where $l x$ is the area of that part of the loop in which $B$ is not zero. By Faraday’s law:

\begin{equation}
    \mathcal{E} = -\frac{d\phi_B}{dt} = -\frac{d}{dt}(B l x) = -B l \frac{dx}{dt} = B l v
\end{equation}

Here, the speed $v = -dx/dt$ represents the speed with which the connecting rod is pulled out of the magnetic field. The electromotive force (emf) $B l v$ sets up a current in the loop given by

\begin{equation}
    i = \frac{\mathcal{E}}{R} = \frac{B l v}{R}
\end{equation}

\begin{figure}[h]
    \centering
    \includegraphics{fig13_30.png}
    \caption{Illustration of the loop and magnetic field.}
    \label{fig:13_30}
\end{figure}

\subsection*{(b)}

The total power delivered to the resistor is just the Joule heat given by

\begin{equation}
    P_I = i^2 R = \frac{B^2 l^2 v^2}{R}
\end{equation}

Note that energy conservation tells us that for steady motion of the rod, the external agent must provide power equal to the Joule heat. This is confirmed by

\begin{equation}
    P = F_3 v = \frac{B^2 l^2 v^2}{R}
\end{equation}

\subsection*{(c)}

The current in the loop produces forces $F_1$, $F_2$, and $F_3$ on the three sides of the loop in accordance with

\begin{equation}
    \mathbf{F} = i \mathbf{l} \times \mathbf{B}
\end{equation}

Because $F_1$ and $F_2$ are equal and opposite, they cancel each other, while $F_3$, which opposes the motion of the sliding rod, is given by equations (4) and (3) in magnitude as

\begin{equation}
    F_3 = i l B \sin 90^\circ = \frac{B^2 l^2 v}{R}
\end{equation}

\end{document}
```

