\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}

\begin{document}

Let the sphere of radius \( R \) rotate about the \( z \)-axis, as shown in Fig. 13.31. Consider a spherical shell of radius \( r \) (\( r < R \)) concentric with the sphere. Consider a volume element symmetrical about the \( z \)-axis. The volume element is given by:

\begin{equation}
dV = 2\pi r^2 \sin \theta \, d\theta \, dr
\end{equation}

where \( \theta \) is the polar angle and \( r \) is the distance of the volume element from the center. The charge \( dq \) residing in the volume element is:

\begin{equation}
dq = \frac{3q}{4\pi R^3} dV
\end{equation}

The current due to the rotation of charge is:

\begin{equation}
di = \omega \cdot \frac{dq}{2\pi} = \frac{3q\omega}{4\pi} \frac{r^2 \sin \theta \, d\theta \, dr}{R^3}
\end{equation}

where we have used equations (2) and (1). The magnetic moment due to \( di \) is:

\begin{align}
d\mu &= (di)(dA) \\
&= \left(\frac{3q\omega r^2 \sin \theta \, d\theta \, dr}{4\pi R^3}\right) (\pi r^2 \sin^2 \theta) \\
&= \frac{3}{4} \frac{\omega q r^4 \, dr \sin^3 \theta \, d\theta}{R^3}
\end{align}

where \( dA \) is the area enclosed by the circle of radius \( r \sin \theta \). The total magnetic moment \( \mu \) is:

\begin{equation}
\mu = \int d\mu = \frac{3}{4} \frac{\omega q}{R^3} \int_0^R r^4 \, dr \int_0^\pi \sin^3 \theta \, d\theta
\end{equation}

Evaluating the integrals, we have:

\begin{align}
\int_0^R r^4 \, dr &= \frac{R^5}{5} \\
\int_0^\pi \sin^3 \theta \, d\theta &= \frac{4}{3}
\end{align}

Thus, the total magnetic moment becomes:

\begin{equation}
\mu = \frac{3}{4} \frac{\omega q}{R^3} \left(\frac{R^5}{5}\right) \left(\frac{4}{3}\right) = \frac{\omega q R^2}{5}
\end{equation}

The angular momentum of a sphere about a diameter is:

\begin{equation}
L = I \omega = \frac{2}{5} m R^2 \omega
\end{equation}

Therefore, the ratio of the magnetic moment to the angular momentum is:

\begin{equation}
\frac{\mu}{L} = \frac{q}{2m}
\end{equation}

\end{document}
```

