```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{graphicx}

\begin{document}

Consider a strip of a conductor of width \( W \) and thickness \( t \) carrying a d.c. current \( i \) in the positive \( x \)-direction along its length, as shown in Fig. 13.32. A magnetic field \( \mathbf{B} \) set up in the \( z \)-direction (into the page) produces a deflection force in the positive \( y \)-direction, as the drift velocity of electrons is in the negative \( x \)-direction. Consequently, charge concentration builds up towards the upper edge of the strip. As the charges collect on one side of the strip, they set up an electric field that opposes the sideways motion of additional charge carriers inside the conductor. This build-up of charges establishes a potential \( V_H \) across the width of the strip, called Hall potential, and the phenomenon is known as the Hall effect. Eventually, equilibrium conditions are reached, and a maximum voltage, known as Hall voltage, is quickly established. The sign of the voltage gives the sign of charge carriers and its magnitude the number density \( n \) of charge carriers.

\begin{figure}[h]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth]{hall_effect.png}
    \caption{Hall effect}
    \label{fig:hall_effect}
\end{figure}

\begin{itemize}
    \item[(a)] The Hall electric field \( E_H \) is given by:
    \[
    E_H = v_d B = \frac{iB}{ne} = \frac{iB}{ne W b} = \frac{100 \times 10}{1.25 \times 10^{30} \times 1.6 \times 10^{-19} \times 10^{-3} \times 0.02} = 2.5 \times 10^{-4} \, \text{V/m}
    \]
    The field is along the positive \( y \)-direction.

    \item[(b)] When equilibrium is established, the Lorentz force is zero:
    \[
    qE + q \mathbf{v}_d \times \mathbf{B} = 0
    \]
    or
    \[
    E = -\mathbf{v}_d \times \mathbf{B}
    \]
    Since \( \mathbf{v}_d \perp \mathbf{B} \), we have:
    \[
    E = -v_d B
    \]
    \[
    E = \frac{V_H}{W} = v_d B = \frac{jB}{ne} = \frac{iB}{Wtn e}
    \]
    Therefore, the number density \( n \) is:
    \[
    n = \frac{iB}{etV_H} = \frac{100 \times 10}{1.6 \times 10^{-19} \times 10^{-3} \times 5 \times 10^{-6}} = 1.25 \times 10^{30} \, \text{m}^{-3}
    \]
\end{itemize}

\end{document}
```

